  "response": "Here are key differences between the Indian and American economies:\n\n1. Economic Size\n- USA: World's largest economy\n- India: Developing economy, 5th largest globally\n\n2. Per Capita Income\n- USA: High (around $70,000)\n- India: Low (around $2,200)\n\n3. Economic Structure\n- USA: Highly service and technology-oriented\n- India: Mix of agriculture, services, and manufacturing\n\n4. GDP Composition\n- USA: Services (80%), Industry (18%), Agriculture (2%)\n- India: Services (54%), Industry (26%), Agriculture (20%)\n\n5. Economic Development Stage\n- USA: Developed, advanced market economy\n- India: Developing, emerging market economy\n\n6. Labor Market\n- USA: High skilled, knowledge-based workforce\n- India: Large young workforce, lower skill levels\n\n7. Innovation and Technology\n- USA: Global leader in technology and innovation\n- India: Growing tech sector, emerging innovation ecosystem\n\n8. Government Role\n- USA: More market-driven, less government intervention\n- India: More government regulations and interventions\n\n9. Foreign Investment\n- USA: Attracts significant global investments\n- India: Emerging investment destination with growing potential\n\n10. Economic Policies\n- USA: Capitalist, free-market approach\n- India: Mixed economic model with socialist elements",
